body:
Can you attach an example that shows the issue? 
When testing the DFT pre-simulation netlist, the testbench requires a lot of force/release operations on internal SI (scan-in).
simplification...
If the COND_0 macro is defined, after release, inst1.i captures **forceval**;   In another branch, releasing signal_0 captures **driven val.** . I think their behavior should remain consistent.
```
`timescale 1ns/1ps
`define COND_0

module inv(
    output o,
    input i);
    assign o = ~i;
endmodule

module dff(
    output reg o,
    input i, clk);
    always_ff@(posedge clk)begin
	    o <= i;
    end
endmodule

module top;
wire signal_1 = 1'b1;
wire signal_0;

reg clk;
wire out;

inv inst0(.i(signal_1), .o(signal_0));
dff inst1(.clk(clk), .i(signal_0), .o(out));

initial begin
`ifdef COND_0
    #1;
    force inst1.i = 1;
    #15;
    release inst1.i;

`else

    #1;
    force signal_0 = 1;
    #15;
    release signal_0;
`endif

    #50;
    $finish();
end

initial begin
    #0;
    clk = 1;
    forever #5 clk = ~clk;
end

endmodule
```

What 'verilator' command line do we use to run your example?
verilator --flatten --cc --top top --timing top.sv

What 'verilator --version' are you using?  Did you try it with the git master version?
Verilator 5.035 devel master(20250324)

What OS and distribution are you using?
rockylinux
May we assist you in trying to fix this in Verilator yourself?
no

